{"title_page": "John Ferguson (clergyman)", "text_new": "{{Other people|John Ferguson}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = John Ferguson\n|image         = \n|image_size    = \n|caption       = \n|birth_date    = {{Birth date|df=yes|1852|12|27}} \n|birth_place   = Shiels, [[Aberdeenshire]], Scotland\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|df=yes|1925|3|1|1852|12|27}}\n|death_place   = [[Kings Cross, New South Wales|Kings Cross]], [[New South Wales]], Australia\n|resting_place = South Head cemetery\n|resting_place_coordinates = \n|residence     = 'Atherton', Kings Cross\n|nationality   = Scottish\n|known_for     = Presbyterian minister, acting principal, school chaplain and chairman\n|education     = [[New College, Edinburgh]]\n|employer      = St Stephen's Church, Sydney\n|occupation    = Presbyterian minister \n|title         = Reverend\n|boards        = [[Presbyterian Ladies' College, Sydney]]<br />[[The Scots College]]<br />[[St Andrew's College, Sydney|St Andrew's College]]\n|spouse        = {{marriage|Isabella Adie |1881|1925}}\n|children      = 5\n}}\n\n'''John Ferguson''' (27 December 1852 \u2013 1 March 1925) was a Scottish-born Australian [[Presbyterian]] minister.\n\n==Early life==\nJohn Ferguson was born on 27 December 1852, at Shiels, [[Aberdeenshire]], [[Scotland]], the third son of William Ferguson, a farmer, and his wife Elizabeth, n\u00e9e Mitchell. He migrated to [[Otago]], [[New Zealand]], with his parents in 1862.<ref name=ADB>{{cite encyclopedia| last = Dougan| first = Alan| encyclopedia =Australian Dictionary of Biography| title = Ferguson, John (1852\u20131925) | url = http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A080512b.htm| accessdate = 26 February 2008| edition = Online| year = 1981| publisher = Melbourne University Press| volume =8| location = Melbourne| pages = 486\u2013487}}</ref>\n\nUpon leaving school at the age of 14, he became a pupil-teacher, and also acted as laboratory assistant in the [[chemistry]] department at the [[University of Otago]]. Ferguson soon realised his desire to enter the [[Christian ministry|ministry]], and subsequently, the congregation of Knox Church at [[Dunedin]], gave him a [[bursary]] to complete the full course at [[New College, Edinburgh|New College]], Edinburgh.<ref name=ADB/>\n\n==Career==\nLicensed as a [[probationer]] by the Free Church presbytery of Deer at [[Stuartfield]], [[Old Deer]], Aberdeenshire, Ferguson returned to Otago and was [[Ordination|ordained]] to the ministry on 20 May 1880. He was then sent to work with the miners at Tuapeka in the [[Central Otago Gold Rush|Central Otago goldfields]].<ref name=ADB/>\n\nFerguson married Isabella Adie, from Old Deer, on 4 February 1881 at Dunedin. He soon became colleague and successor to A. Stobo at [[Invercargill]], where he remained in full charge for fourteen years. In August 1894 Ferguson was inducted to St Stephen's, [[Phillip Street, Sydney|Phillip Street]], Sydney, the largest Presbyterian congregation in Australia. His ministry in Sydney was very successful.<ref name=ADB/>\n\nFerguson took a full part in Australian religious and public life, becoming [[Moderator of the General Assembly|moderator-general]] in 1909. His inaugural address, published as ''The Economic Value of the Gospel'', caused controversy in [[Melbourne]] and praise from trade union leaders.<ref name=ADB/> [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] politician [[Billy Hughes|William Morris (Billy) Hughes]] (who was to become [[Prime Minister of Australia|Prime Minister]] in 1915),<ref name=ADBHughes>{{cite encyclopedia| last = Fitzhardinge| first = L.F.| encyclopedia =Australian Dictionary of Biography| title = Hughes, William Morris (Billy) (1862\u20131952) | url = http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A090395b.htm| accessdate = 26 February 2008| edition = Online| year = 1983| publisher = Melbourne University Press| volume =9| location = Melbourne| pages = 393\u2013400}}</ref> said: {{quote|The new moderator preaches a gospel all sufficient, all powerful. He grapples with the problems of poverty \u2026 he insists on justice being done, though the heavens fall. I advise every citizen to read every word of it.<ref name=ADB/>}}\n\nAs the senior Presbyterian chaplain in [[New South Wales]], Ferguson preached on many special occasions, including the arrival of [[HMAS Australia (1911)|H.M.A.S. Australia]] and the memorial services at the end of the [[Second Boer War|South African War]] and [[World War I]].<ref name=ADB/> Ferguson's [[ecumenical]] interests led him to seek an audience with the Pope on a visit to Rome in 1914, an action that evoked much criticism in Sydney.<ref name=GH>{{cite book| last = McFarlane| first = John| title = The Golden Hope: Presbyterian Ladies' College, Sydney 1888\u20131988| year = 1988| publisher = P.L.C Council, Presbyterian Ladies' College, Sydney| location = Croydon, NSW| isbn = 0-9597340-1-5| chapter =Firm Foundations 1888\u20131919| page = 23}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 May 1913, following the resignation of [[Andrew Harper]], Ferguson was appointed Senior Chaplain and Chairman of the exclusive [[Presbyterian Ladies' College, Sydney]] Council, retiring in 1923 due to ill health. Whilst in this role, he actively worked towards the planning and establishment of the [[Pymble Ladies' College|Presbyterian Ladies' College, Pymble]] in 1916, a branch of the Presbyterian Ladies' College, Sydney.<ref name=GH/> He was also the first chairman of the board of the [[Australian Inland Mission]], a member of the Council of [[The Scots College]] and St Andrew's Theological College, and Vice-President of the Highland Society of New South Wales.<ref name=ADB/> He was also to become the Acting Principal of [[St Andrew's College, Sydney|St Andrew's Theological College]] at the [[University of Sydney]] in 1917.<ref name=PLC/>\n\nIt is said that Ferguson was a \"tall, dark-haired man, with a drooping moustache and a commanding presence. An attractive preacher, with a genial and informal friendliness, he seldom forgot a face or a name and few entered St Stephen's without a warm personal greeting. He was admired and respected by all the Churches.\"<ref name=GH/>\n\n==Death==\nIn October 1924, Ferguson collapsed in the [[pulpit]] of St. Stephen's Church and subsequently died at his home, 'Atherton', on [[Bayswater Road, Sydney|Bayswater Road]], on 1 March 1925. He was survived by his wife, three sons, including [[John Alexander Ferguson|Sir John]], judge of the [[Industrial Court of New South Wales|New South Wales Industrial Commission]] and author of the ''Australian National Bibliography''; Eustace, a notable [[pathologist]] and [[entomologist]], and by two daughters. He was buried at [[Sydney Heads#South Head|South Head]] Cemetery in Sydney.<ref name=ADB/>\n\n==Legacy==\nFollowing Ferguson's death, a memorial hall and tablet were erected at St Stephen's Church, Sydney in his honour.<ref name=ADB/> Ferguson [[House system|House]] at the Presbyterian Ladies' College, Sydney is also named after him.<ref name=PLC>{{cite web|url= http://www.plc.nsw.edu.au/public2/house_system.asp|title= House System|accessdate= 26 February 2008|work= History|publisher= Presbyterian Ladies' College, Sydney |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070927004939/http://www.plc.nsw.edu.au/public2/house_system.asp |archivedate = 27 September 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Notable descendants==\n* [[John Alexander Ferguson]], (Sir), compiled the first [http://catalogue.nla.gov.au/Record/2045408 Bibliography of Australia].\n* [[Eustace William Ferguson]], pathologist and entomologist\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Australian Presbyterians]]\n*[[Notable Aberdonians]]\n*[[Presbyterian Church of Australia]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n{{Presbyterian Ladies' College, Sydney}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ferguson, John}}\n[[Category:1852 births]]\n[[Category:1925 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian educators]]\n[[Category:Australian Presbyterian ministers]]\n[[Category:Ministers of the Free Church of Scotland]]\n[[Category:People from Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:Scottish emigrants to colonial Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|John Ferguson}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = John Ferguson\n|image         = \n|image_size    = \n|caption       = \n|birth_date    = {{Birth date|df=yes|1852|12|27}} \n|birth_place   = Shiels, [[Aberdeenshire]], Scotland\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|df=yes|1925|3|1|1852|12|27}}\n|death_place   = [[Kings Cross, New South Wales|Kings Cross]], [[New South Wales]], Australia\n|resting_place = South Head cemetery\n|resting_place_coordinates = \n|residence     = 'Atherton', Kings Cross\n|nationality   = Scottish\n|known_for     = Presbyterian Minister; Acting Principal, School Chaplain and chairman\n|education     = [[New College, Edinburgh]]\n|employer      = St Stephen's Church, Sydney\n|occupation    = Presbyterian minister \n|title         = Reverend\n|boards        = [[Presbyterian Ladies' College, Sydney]]<br />[[The Scots College]]<br />[[St Andrew's College, Sydney|St Andrew's College]]\n|spouse        = {{marriage|Isabella Adie |1881|1925}}\n|children      = 5\n}}\n\n'''John Ferguson''' (27 December 1852 \u2013 1 March 1925) was a Scottish-born Australian [[Presbyterian]] minister.\n\n==Early life==\nJohn Ferguson was born on 27 December 1852, at Shiels, [[Aberdeenshire]], [[Scotland]], the third son of William Ferguson, a farmer, and his wife Elizabeth, n\u00e9e Mitchell. He migrated to [[Otago]], [[New Zealand]], with his parents in 1862.<ref name=ADB>{{cite encyclopedia| last = Dougan| first = Alan| encyclopedia =Australian Dictionary of Biography| title = Ferguson, John (1852\u20131925) | url = http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A080512b.htm| accessdate = 26 February 2008| edition = Online| year = 1981| publisher = Melbourne University Press| volume =8| location = Melbourne| pages = 486\u2013487}}</ref>\n\nUpon leaving school at the age of 14, he became a pupil-teacher, and also acted as laboratory assistant in the [[chemistry]] department at the [[University of Otago]]. Ferguson soon realised his desire to enter the [[Christian ministry|ministry]], and subsequently, the congregation of Knox Church at [[Dunedin]], gave him a [[bursary]] to complete the full course at [[New College, Edinburgh|New College]], Edinburgh.<ref name=ADB/>\n\n==Career==\nLicensed as a [[probationer]] by the Free Church presbytery of Deer at [[Stuartfield]], [[Old Deer]], Aberdeenshire, Ferguson returned to Otago and was [[Ordination|ordained]] to the ministry on 20 May 1880. He was then sent to work with the miners at Tuapeka in the [[Central Otago Gold Rush|Central Otago goldfields]].<ref name=ADB/>\n\nFerguson married Isabella Adie, from Old Deer, on 4 February 1881 at Dunedin. He soon became colleague and successor to A. Stobo at [[Invercargill]], where he remained in full charge for fourteen years. In August 1894 Ferguson was inducted to St Stephen's, [[Phillip Street, Sydney|Phillip Street]], Sydney, the largest Presbyterian congregation in Australia. His ministry in Sydney was very successful.<ref name=ADB/>\n\nFerguson took a full part in Australian religious and public life, becoming [[Moderator of the General Assembly|moderator-general]] in 1909. His inaugural address, published as ''The Economic Value of the Gospel'', caused controversy in [[Melbourne]] and praise from trade union leaders.<ref name=ADB/> [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] politician [[Billy Hughes|William Morris (Billy) Hughes]] (who was to become [[Prime Minister of Australia|Prime Minister]] in 1915),<ref name=ADBHughes>{{cite encyclopedia| last = Fitzhardinge| first = L.F.| encyclopedia =Australian Dictionary of Biography| title = Hughes, William Morris (Billy) (1862\u20131952) | url = http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A090395b.htm| accessdate = 26 February 2008| edition = Online| year = 1983| publisher = Melbourne University Press| volume =9| location = Melbourne| pages = 393\u2013400}}</ref> said: {{quote|The new moderator preaches a gospel all sufficient, all powerful. He grapples with the problems of poverty \u2026 he insists on justice being done, though the heavens fall. I advise every citizen to read every word of it.<ref name=ADB/>}}\n\nAs the senior Presbyterian chaplain in [[New South Wales]], Ferguson preached on many special occasions, including the arrival of [[HMAS Australia (1911)|H.M.A.S. Australia]] and the memorial services at the end of the [[Second Boer War|South African War]] and [[World War I]].<ref name=ADB/> Ferguson's [[ecumenical]] interests led him to seek an audience with the Pope on a visit to Rome in 1914, an action that evoked much criticism in Sydney.<ref name=GH>{{cite book| last = McFarlane| first = John| title = The Golden Hope: Presbyterian Ladies' College, Sydney 1888\u20131988| year = 1988| publisher = P.L.C Council, Presbyterian Ladies' College, Sydney| location = Croydon, NSW| isbn = 0-9597340-1-5| chapter =Firm Foundations 1888\u20131919| page = 23}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 May 1913, following the resignation of [[Andrew Harper]], Ferguson was appointed Senior Chaplain and Chairman of the exclusive [[Presbyterian Ladies' College, Sydney]] Council, retiring in 1923 due to ill health. Whilst in this role, he actively worked towards the planning and establishment of the [[Pymble Ladies' College|Presbyterian Ladies' College, Pymble]] in 1916, a branch of the Presbyterian Ladies' College, Sydney.<ref name=GH/> He was also the first chairman of the board of the [[Australian Inland Mission]], a member of the Council of [[The Scots College]] and St Andrew's Theological College, and Vice-President of the Highland Society of New South Wales.<ref name=ADB/> He was also to become the Acting Principal of [[St Andrew's College, Sydney|St Andrew's Theological College]] at the [[University of Sydney]] in 1917.<ref name=PLC/>\n\nIt is said that Ferguson was a \"tall, dark-haired man, with a drooping moustache and a commanding presence. An attractive preacher, with a genial and informal friendliness, he seldom forgot a face or a name and few entered St Stephen's without a warm personal greeting. He was admired and respected by all the Churches.\"<ref name=GH/>\n\n==Death==\nIn October 1924, Ferguson collapsed in the [[pulpit]] of St. Stephen's Church and subsequently died at his home, 'Atherton', on [[Bayswater Road, Sydney|Bayswater Road]], on 1 March 1925. He was survived by his wife, three sons including [[John Alexander Ferguson|Sir John]], Judge of the [[Industrial Court of New South Wales|New South Wales Industrial Commission]] and author of the Australian National Bibliography; Eustace, a notable [[pathologist]] and [[entomologist]], and by two daughters. He was buried at [[Sydney Heads#South Head|South Head]] Cemetery in Sydney.<ref name=ADB/>\n\n==Legacy==\nFollowing Ferguson's death, a memorial hall and tablet were erected at St Stephen's Church, Sydney in his honour.<ref name=ADB/> Ferguson [[House system|House]] at the Presbyterian Ladies' College, Sydney is also named after him.<ref name=PLC>{{cite web|url= http://www.plc.nsw.edu.au/public2/house_system.asp|title= House System|accessdate= 26 February 2008|work= History|publisher= Presbyterian Ladies' College, Sydney |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070927004939/http://www.plc.nsw.edu.au/public2/house_system.asp |archivedate = 27 September 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Notable descendants==\n* [[John Alexander Ferguson]], (Sir), compiled the first [http://catalogue.nla.gov.au/Record/2045408 Bibliography of Australia].\n* [[Eustace William Ferguson]], pathologist and entomologist\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Australian Presbyterians]]\n*[[Notable Aberdonians]]\n*[[Presbyterian Church of Australia]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n{{Presbyterian Ladies' College, Sydney}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSOR